stomizers. So, existing tests only bind properties but don’t handle auto-configuration or customizers. But if I want to use a public API? The DataWebAutoConfiguration constructor is package-private, so I can’t access it outside the package.\\n\\n**Evaluating test strategies**\\n\\nI’m thinking about a testing strategy focusing on integration versus checking for duplicates in success flow. The user asked about testing new features, and I realize the existing listener success is mostly covered, but it doesn’t incorporate the @Timed annotation. Maybe having two tests is excessive. I wonder if I could consolidate and just keep one functional test for the TimedAnnotations instead of retesting already established logic flows. Adding a new direct test for TimedAnnotations seems more efficient.\\n\\n**Analyzing test coverage**\\n\\nI need to analyze the current coverage and consider writing tests for the new functional feature involving the @Timed annotation. My concern is about the extraTags array in the assertion and how class-level annotations interact with method annotations. It might be beneficial to name the test something like `timedAnnotationsPreferRepositoryMethodAnnotationsAndFallBackToTypeAnnotations` to cover method precedence and fallback in one go, without duplicates. I also need to ensure I've imported the right classes and handle the assertions correctly.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0f31f5ceec0fa013016a0cdb472aec8197af355c532cf9bd3f\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqDNtgr3PNi7fB0dR4-h2W1HMv5orJ1rdKBMoB-GUhrShTPKYt0U5KKYATqzcKBbswnKRROKjMSdOpilLfF3IoQ5nNQIaIZz-bodH4Mf2dOVEtQE8MeaFfNyiZ2lEO6076fpTDX-ALSRVNNcRosbvAg4NxYpvi5Uk7ek7w4c_wlUS1H9pHwsmKW3-wbiyH07avB1SQGnm8wFCy-4YxXDM0Rf9AQ4el74g_wn6EdWyvnT3a8tRrls0aGKaWa1Kl8OQoIS5oDvt6kEXMy1WWy951DeMElMbJfBSxVEps0wtCZINo-brRdz2iBpRwsEIZma3iROHy7woN5l0KkAyK8wdDtdg1oEtQmRXVKwRlytPfH84Drha5p4_JGvMsde1QnuShgUcdrk-klWPDnyATtRYz3t-CKQqTNTIFkaUcHgKAKBgf-UW9E-uWFH2678y